change.subject: Convert all incoming protocol numbers to string
change.commitMessage:
Convert all incoming protocol numbers to string

PostgreSQL is more sensitive for types than MySQL when it selects
something from columns in database. So it fails when it tries to
select from string field comparing with integer value.

Added unit test to verify conversion of protocol numbers to
strings.

Closes-bug:#1381379

(cherry picked from commit bc34f26302faea116be7e61051c32f8787530836)

Conflicts:
	neutron/tests/unit/test_extension_security_group.py

Change-Id: I0a29595403a07c66888871088d5549705a097f68

change.subject: double check admin password when update user password
change.commitMessage:
double check admin password when update user password

Add a new setting to enable a new textbox field on the Edit
User form that will double check the logged-in Admin
user's password. This setting is False by default.

For example if the logged-in admin leaves an unattended computer,
someone can change the password of the logged in user successfully.

Change-Id: Icafa8ce8ab30ec43d3f6419a77118a634a163870
Closes-Bug: #1387372

comment:
Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

I chatted with Steve in IRC.  I think this is a good change.  Here's my summary of what we discussed:

What I'm taking away is that the command line is generally vulnerable to this sort of attack, unless admins aren't using command history or id/pw in environment variables.  Passing in the extra password parm doesn't really solve anything in that case, because if they can issue the command they have the password anyway.

The attack I was suggesting could be opened up in my previous comment isn't a new hole,  it's just that we'll have to be careful as we move the UI to a client side implementation we make sure we don't allow this check to be bypassed by simple use of a browser debugger.  We'll just need to keep it server side.
